    public class TableViewSeries
extends TableViewSeriesBase
    A view that allows selecting, reordering and renaming the DataSeries from a DataTable based on a list of series indexes or labels.
    Author:
    O. J. Coleman

      • getSelected

        public ListSet<String>[] getSelected()
        Description copied from class: TableViewSeriesBase
        Implementations must return the list/set of selected series labels and, optionally, the corresponding new labels. The ListSet at index is the label in the input table, the ListSet at index 1 is the new label. If a label is not available in the input table it will be ignored.

      • renameSeries

        Parameters:

        Returns:
        This data table view.

      • renameSeriesPP

        public TableViewSeries renameSeriesPP(String prefix,
                                      String postfix)
        Relabels the series in the input table by prepending and appending the specified prefix and postfix to their labels. If the prefix or postfix contain '\\oi' this will be replaced by the (original) index of the series. An '\\oi' may be followed by numerals to indicate an offset, for example "my\\oi5pf" will give strings "my5pf", my6pf", "my7pf" and so on.
        Parameters:
        prefix - The string to prepend to each label. May be null or an empty string.
        postfix - The string to append to each label. May be null or an empty string.
        Returns:
        This data table view.

      • setSeriesRE

        public TableViewSeries setSeriesRE(Pattern pattern,
                                   String renamePattern)
        Selects series from the input table whose labels match the given regular expression pattern.
        Parameters:
        pattern - The regular expression pattern to use to match series labels.
        renamePattern - The replacement pattern (with $N referring to capture groups in 'pattern'). If renamePattern contains '\\oi' or '\\ni' it will be replaced by the original or new index of the series respectively. An '\\oi' or '\\ni' may be followed by numerals to indicate an offset, for example "my\\ni5pf" will give strings "my5pf", my6pf", "my7pf" and so on.
        Returns:
        This data table view.
